# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2-unlimited
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-album] All lyrics are written by Asphodel; all music is composed by Alexis Damien & Pin-Up Went Down.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-album] The album has been well received by the critics and the public alike.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-album] *AGM* webzine, in a positive review, has praised Asphodel's and Alexis Damien's vocals, the album's ever-changing musical direction and its lyrics, ending their review stating "it's one of the most promising first-time debut releases of all time of avant-garde music.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-album] It has a 17 out 20 approval rate at Spirit of Metal.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-discography] This is the discography of 2 Unlimited, a Eurodance project founded in 1991 by Belgian producers Jean-Paul DeCoster and Phil Wilde and fronted by Dutch rapper Ray Slijngaard and Dutch vocalist Anita Doth.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-discography] With global sales of over 18 million units, 2 Unlimited is one of the biggest selling groups from the Netherlands and Belgium.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-discography] "—" denotes items that did not chart or were not released.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-discography] "—" denotes a title that did not chart, or was not released in that territory.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-discography] 2 Unlimited has a total of 4 songs which appear in the *Dance Dance Revolution* arcade series.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-discography] A cover version of the original "Twilight Zone" was featured on *Dancing Stage Featuring Disney's Rave*, while an official remix of "Twilight Zone" was featured in *DDRMAX Dance Dance Revolution 6thMix* and two other arcade releases.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-discography] Additionally, the original version of "No Limit" appears in *Just Dance 3*, while the original version of "Tribal Dance" appears in *Just Dance 4*.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited-discography] The Super Nintendo game Bio-Metal had its soundtrack for the American release reworked entirely of remixes from the 1992 album Get Ready!.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Jean-Paul De Coster and Phil Wilde met in their hometown of Antwerp, Belgium, and created 2 Unlimited in their studio, initially without any performers or vocalists.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Their first collaboration under the name of Bizz Nizz resulted in a single called "Don't Miss The Party Line" which entered the top 10 in the UK.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The two then decided to continue to work together.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] De Coster and Wilde had initially created an instrumental track called "Get Ready for This" in May 1991, but they wanted to try out some rap vocals on it.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] They were so pleased with the result that they agreed to work with them as a duo, and so 2 Unlimited was born.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 2 Unlimited were signed to Byte Records (Belgium) and licensed to many other record labels worldwide, including PWL Continental in the UK, ZYX in Germany, Switzerland, and Austria, Scorpio in France, etc.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Their first single, "Get Ready for This", was well received in their home markets, peaking at No.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 2 hit record in both Australia and the UK.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] *Billboard* Hot 100 chart, three years after its original release.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] A follow-up single, "Twilight Zone", followed in January 1992, topping the charts in the Netherlands and performing well in many other markets, reaching No.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In the United States, it only reached No.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] To capitalize on this success, the album *Get Ready!* was released on 24 February 1992, featuring the first two singles and seven more new tracks, including two ballads.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Two further singles were released from the album: "Workaholic" and "The Magic Friend".
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In the US, the album received a Gold certification for sales of 500,000 units in 1995.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 2 Unlimited's lead single from their second album, the similarly titled "No Limit", was released in January 1993.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The repetitive nature of the song helped it become their most successful single to date and by far the best remembered by the general public.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] It topped the charts in Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, and the UK.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In Germany, it was certified Platinum for sales of 500,000 units.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The track received modest airplay on North American radio stations, reaching the top 25 in the US dance charts.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] By 1996, worldwide sales had reached 2.3 million units.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] "Tribal Dance" was released as a single shortly before the album *No Limits!* hit stores in May 1993.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] It became a top 5 hit in Austria, Australia, Belgium, France, Germany, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, and the UK.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In Germany, "Tribal Dance" was certified Gold for sales of over 250,000 units.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Three further singles were issued from the second album: "Faces", which was considerably different in pace to previous releases; "Maximum Overdrive"; and a re-recorded version of "Let the Beat Control Your Body".
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] For the French edition of this single, the lyrics were changed to "Let the bass control your body", in a version named "Bass Edit", to avoid any confusion with the slang word "bite" (meaning "penis").
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In May 1993, the duo received a World Music Award for World's Best-Selling Dutch Artists.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 2 Unlimited's second album proved more successful than their first, entering the top five of album charts in Austria, Australia, Germany, the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, and Switzerland.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In the UK, the album reached the top of the album chart.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] By 1996, its total sales had reached three million units, including 592,000 units in the GSA region (Germany, Switzerland, Austria).
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Despite the phenomenal success the duo were enjoying in the UK, they were criticised heavily by the music industry, and the British press dubbed them "2 Untalented".
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In May 1994, the duo's tenth single, "The Real Thing", was released, and it proved that their fans were still interested, as they sent the single to No.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 1 in the Netherlands, as well as the top 5 in Belgium, Germany, and Norway.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The same month, they received an award for World's Best-Selling Benelux Recording Artists at the World Music Awards.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] While the duo's third album, *Real Things*, shot to No.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 1 in the Netherlands and the UK, it also managed to land in the top 5 in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden, and Switzerland.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The record was certified Gold in the UK for sales of over 100,000 units.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The second single from *Real Things*, "No One", despite being a straightforward pop song, didn't prevent it from reaching No.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In March 1995, while the follow-up single, "Here I Go", was another top 5 hit in the Netherlands, the band's commercial success seemed to be declining elsewhere—the song only made it to the top 20 in Austria, Belgium, and Sweden.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The fourth and final single, the ballad "Nothing Like the Rain", was not as successful and was not released in many territories, including the UK.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In May 1995, 2 Unlimited won their third World Music Award in a row, this time for World's Best-Selling Benelux Artist.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In October 1995, 2 Unlimited released their first compilation album, *Hits Unlimited*, prompting rumours that they were about to split up.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The first single, "Do What's Good for Me", entered the top 5 in Finland, and the top 20 in the Netherlands and the UK.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Despite their insistence that they were planning a world tour, in April 1996, shortly after the release of the single "Jump for Joy", both Slijngaard and Doth decided not to extend their five-year contract and left 2 Unlimited.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] It later emerged that after having spent so much time together, they were no longer getting on as well as they once had, and there was disagreement about the future sound of the band.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] They had asked for more creative input and they also felt that they were not getting a fair share of the huge amount of money being earned by the project.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] As no agreement was reached, they each went their separate ways before a final single, "Spread Your Love", was released in June 1996.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] As they still owned the rights to the name 2 Unlimited, De Coster and Wilde recruited two new (again Dutch) singers, Romy van Ooijen (b.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 18 November 1971) and Marjon van Iwaarden (b.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 18 June 1974), in order to capitalise on previous success.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The first single released under the new lineup, "Wanna Get Up", did well in the Netherlands, reaching No.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] A remix by Sash!, for UK release, reached No.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The album *II* was released in April 1998.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] It was not as successful as previous studio albums, nor were the subsequent singles, "Edge of Heaven" and "Never Surrender".
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In 1999, both van Ooijen and van Iwaarden left 2 Unlimited.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In 2000, Byte Records released the remix singles "No Limit" and "Twilight Zone".
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] A remix album was to be released that year, but some master tapes were stolen from Byte and taken to Russia, where they were released as a bootleg compilation.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Also that year, 2 Unlimited made their first appearance on the Eurodance compilation *Dancemania* series, specifically its *Speed* sub-series, with their song "Twilight Zone", 'B4 Za Beat Mix'.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In 2001, Byte finally released "Greatest Hits Remixes", featuring many new remixes.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Some of the tracks from the stolen master tapes released in Russia were not included.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In 2002, *Trance Remixes: Special Edition* was released in Japan, featuring many more new remixes not included in the previous compilation.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In the following years, many "best of" compilations have been released in various territories, often with new remixes.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Most notably, ZYX Records released "No Limit 2.3" in 2003 and it was a moderate hit, reaching no.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] It was promoted by a new duo, Débora Remagen and James Giscombe.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] They were being lined up as a 2 Unlimited "version 3".
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] They still perform, mainly in Eastern Europe, but are not allowed to use their own voices.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] A new CD and DVD set containing all 2 Unlimited music videos, called *The Complete History*, was released in 2004, along with a single, "Tribal Dance 2.4" (originally released on 12" vinyl in November 2003 as "Tribal Dance 2.3").
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] 2005 saw the release of *The Refreshed Album* in Mexico, featuring stunning artwork, but the same remixes found on previous remix albums.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In 2006, the DVD was re-packaged with a different CD, *Greatest Remix Hits*, and released in Australia.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The following years saw this package re-released in Argentina, Denmark, Sweden, Asia, and South Africa.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Having both continued to perform their old hits separately in nightclubs and university student unions around the world, the original performers Slijngaard and Doth reunited on 11 April 2009, to perform together for the first time in 13 years at the "I Love the 90s" concert in Hasselt, Belgium.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] According to a radio interview with Slijngaard, Jean-Paul De Coster did not give permission for the duo to perform under the name 2 Unlimited; however, Phil Wilde attended the gig and provided help with preparing backing tracks.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] On 30 April 2009, Slijngaard and Doth performed five songs at the Radio 538 Queen's Day concert at Museumplein in Amsterdam.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] On 8 June, they were awarded "Most Popular Act of the 1990s", based on the number of weeks in the Dutch Top 40; on 25 September, they performed as a support act for Milk Inc. at the Sportpaleis in Antwerp.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] On 29 December 2009, it was announced that the duo would release a new single in 2010, called "In Da Name of Love", as Ray & Anita.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] It was released as a CD single in the Netherlands through Spinnin' Records on 22 January 2010.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] On 30 April 2010, a new single was presented during the Dutch Queen's Day, called "Still Unlimited".
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In July 2011, Ray & Anita invited fans to be part of the video for "Nothing 2 Lose" in Amsterdam.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Fans applied via email and were selected randomly.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The video with the fans was shot on 28 July.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The single was released at the end of August 2011.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The single is also the lead track for the soundtrack of the film *Amsterdam Heavy*.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In the same month, Ray & Anita headlined the "I Love the 90's" stage at Tomorrowland in Belgium.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] On 11 July 2012, it was announced that Ray & Anita would be working again with Belgian producer De Coster under the name 2 Unlimited.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] On 30 March 2013, Slijngaard and Doth performed their first full concert as 2 Unlimited with their band in Belgium at Antwerps Sportpaleis.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The duo released a remixed version of their very first single, "Get Ready for This", on 28 October 2013.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] The song was remixed by DJ Steve Aoki and was included on their *Greatest Hits* album.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] In 2014, 2 Unlimited gave concerts at ten festivals that together made up Acceleration 2014, which combined top class car and bike racing with music and entertainment.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] On 20 April 2016, 2 Unlimited announced that Doth was leaving the band at the end of 2016 to embark on a solo career.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] Doth was to be replaced by another singer, whose identity was not revealed right away.
[src:2-unlimited/2-unlimited] On 13 August 2016, Kim Vergouwen was revealed as Doth's replacement via Slijngaard's Facebook page.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 plays a variety of music from the 1980s to the present, including dance, R&B, pop, and rock.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The music selection is primarily based on the Dutch Top 40 chart.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] During morning and drive times, the station features more talk-intensive programming.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 was established in 1992 as the successor to Sky Hitradio, a sister station of Sky Radio that operated from July to December 11, 1992.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] It was initiated by a group of former Radio Veronica employees, led by Lex Harding together with Peter de Jager, Rob Out, Ton Lathouwers, Ab Trik and Erik de Zwart.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The station began broadcasting on December 11, 1992, from a villa in Bussum.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The name “Radio 538” refers to the wavelength (538m: 557 kHz) on which Radio Veronica broadcast in the 1970s.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The first presenters included Rick van Velthuysen, Wessel van Diepen, Erik de Zwart, Michael Pilarczyk, Will Luikinga, and Corné Klijn.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 initially broadcast from Studio Concordia in Bussum, which was also used by the Veronica program *Countdown* in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In the late 1990s, the station moved to a studio complex near the town hall in Hilversum.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Since December 1, 2012, the entire 538 Group has been located in the 4400 m2 NCRV building at Bergweg 70 in Hilversum.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Initially, from its start in 1992 until 1995, Radio 538 was only available via cable.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] A request to be allowed to broadcast over the air was rejected at that time.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Following a media campaign during which 320,000 signatures were collected Radio 538 acquired its over-the-air frequency in 1995 – or more precisely, a collection of several regional frequencies.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2003, Radio 538 was granted a new nationwide frequency, 102 MHz (FM).
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] 538 had to pay €57 million for the new frequencies.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 1995, Lex Harding started TMF (The Music Factory), a TV station, and Erik de Zwart became the new chairman of 538.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] At the end of 2002, Erik de Zwart left to go to competitor Noordzee FM.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Jan-Willem Brüggenwirth became the new chairman.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In December 2003 Radio 538 was sold to Advent International, Lex Harding retaining 10% of the shares.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In May 2005 Radio 538 was sold in its entirety to Talpa Holding, owned by Dutch media mogul John de Mol.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In June 2007 De Mol sold the TV and radio assets of Talpa to RTL Nederland and became shareholder of RTL Nederland.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 managed in 10 years to win a substantial market share.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In April/May 2004, the station nudged market leader Sky Radio to the throne.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Nowadays 538 still competes with NPO Radio 2 and NPO 3FM as the most listened radio station in the Netherlands.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The marketing share is between 10 and 12 percent.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2002, 2004 and 2009 Radio 538 won the Marconi Award for best radio station.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In Flanders, a Flemish version of Radio 538 launched on cable in February 1999, pending the airwave frequency allocation for national commercial radio, which in the late nineties was announced by the Flemish government in 2000.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] When in 2000 was no clear procedure for a given frequency, Radio 538 withdrew from Flanders.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2011 Talpa worked together with Finnish media conglomerate Sanoma to buy the Dutch activities of SBS Broadcasting from German broadcaster ProSiebenSat.1 Media.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] As part of that deal De Mol sold his shares in RTL Nederland to the RTL Group, retaining the ownership of Radio 538 and its sister station SLAM!FM.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2014 Radio 538 started with some new programs.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] De Avondploeg, De Show Zonder Naam and Jurk!FM.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2018, the station announced that it would stop carrying the flagship Dutch Top 40 chart.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Prior to this, it has been discontinued on FM signal for quite some time.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The replacement will be named 538TOP50, and it is compiled based on the selection from 150,000 538Members, airplay on Spotify, YouTube and all the Dutch music stations, alongside Talpa's app JUKE.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In the beginning, the station focused mainly on youth with slogans like, "The station of a young generation".
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] With the advent of disc jockeys such as Edwin Evers, the target group expanded, and the station became wider.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] A new Alarmschijf and Dancesmash still ran weekly.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The listener can also help decide which music is played in the program Maak 't or kraak 't and in past the Top 538.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Jingles for the station is recorded by Wessel van Diepen, Rick Romijn and Kimberly van de Berkt.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Nowadays, the station makes commercial hit radio for young people in the broadest sense of the word.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The format consists of Top 40 music, dance, Contemporary R&B and "throwbacks", supplemented with information and entertainment by DJs.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The morning shows (4am-12pm) feature a mix of current and classic hits.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The afternoon and nighttime shows focus more on current hits.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] From the launch in 1992 and until 1994, Radio 538 was distributed via cable.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 1994 the station submitted a request for an FM license, however larger stations (such as Radio 538 and SkyRadio) were not granted any FM licenses at that time in favor of smaller, local radio stations.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Subsequently, Radio 538 started a media campaign, where a total of 320,000 signatures were collected and in 1995 Radio 538 received license to broadcast on FM on the frequency (103.0 MHz, from Lelystad).
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On 1 January 1998 the station moved to another frequency package, with different frequencies in different regions.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] At the air distribution in 2003 (called Zerobase) Radio 538 received a new nationwide FM network.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 promotes its frequencies as "102 FM".
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Due to the lack of available FM frequencies in the south Limburg region, it was also rebroadcast on 891 kHz mediumwave from a transmitter in Hulsberg.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 can also be received via Digitenne and the whole of Europe via satellite and worldwide via the Internet.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Previously it was available on mobile phones via UMTS (on the portals of KPN i-mode and Vodafone Live) and in Limburg on AM 891 kHz, 336 m.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 also transmits a TMC signal from traffic for route navigation.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] From 30 August until 23 November 2011 Radio 538 was broadcast on 106.0 MHz from the tower of Ping FM in the Belgian Lanaken, for the region of Limburg-Maastricht from 12 midnight until 7 pm.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Ping FM was eventually ordered by the Vlaamse Regulator voor de Media (Flemish Regulator for the Media) to stop the retransmission of programs of Radio 538.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In mid-September 2014 the programs of 538 can be heard via Ping FM.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] During the day on weekdays, on Thursday, till Sunday also few hours in the evening and on Saturday and Sunday mornings.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In August 2016, it was reported that Radio 538 would cease to broadcast via mediumwave 891 kHz within one month, as it is now well-received via cable, DAB+ and the internet in the south Limburg region.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] From 26 October 2016 this transmitting is indeed ceased.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Every hour also on the half-hour, the news is broadcast, which is provided by the Algemeen Nederland's Persbureau (ANP).
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] At other times the news is read by newscasters associated with the ANP.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 1999, Radio 538 started the hip-hop and contemporary R&B program *Juize*, which developed into the radio station Juize.FM on 18 July 2004.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Since 1 July 2005, Juize FM is broadcast in most of the Netherlands by cable and has also started running shows with presenters.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2011, Radio 538 created a sister television station called TV 538.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Until 2011 538 organized annually at Queen's Day a big party on the Museumplein in Amsterdam.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Several artists from home and abroad joined there by from 12pm and the day was traditionally ended with a grand musical and visual spectacle of a well-known DJs.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] At this event, some 300,000 visitors came off.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In November 2011 the city of Amsterdam decided that this Queen's Day Party was not allowed to take place in connection with safety.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Initially, the 538-party in 2012 at the square near RAI Amsterdam will be held, but in January of that year it was decided to call off the whole party.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] After an evaluation of the edition 2012 the city council decided in 2013 to pursue the creation of more scattered, smaller celebrations on Queen's Day.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Since King's Day 2014 the big party finds annual place again, but at a different location; in Breda on the Chasséveld.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] From 2005 to 2012 538 reached annual the 538 Schoolawards from the best school in the Netherlands.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] All secondary schools in the Netherlands were able to register for this election, after which the students could vote for their school.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The schools with the most votes went together into battle in the final to win a big school and the 538 School awards title.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2006 the Zwijsen College in Veghel won.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2007 the prize was won by Adelbert College in Wassenaar, in 2008 by CSG Willem van Oranje in Oud-Beijerland, in 2009 by the Baudartius College in Zutphen, in 2010 by Het Baarnsch Lyceum in Baarn, in 2011 by Sg Spieringshoek in Schiedam and in 2012 by Kalsbeek College in Woerden.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] From 2013 SLAM!FM took the School Awards over from 538.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On 9 July 2011 538 organized, in collaboration with Spa Reine, the beach festival Turn up the Beach.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] This first edition on the beach of IJmuiden was a great success.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On 14 July 2012 538 organized, in collaboration with Pepsi, the second edition of Turn up the Beach.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The third edition of Turn up the beach was on 13 July 2013.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On 22 December 2012 Radio 538 and RTL 5 organized the price show and music festival 538 JingleBall in the Ziggo Dome.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] This show was organized because Radio 538 had existed for 20 years in 2012.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The second edition of 538 Jingle Ball was on 21 December 2013; this time there was only dance music, run by Dutch DJs.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Even before the second edition was held Radio 538 had announced that there would be a third edition of 538 JingleBall.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] If the Netherlands is joining a UEFA European Championship or FIFA World Cup, Radio 538 organizes the 538 Oranjeplein on the Museumplein in Amsterdam.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] People can watch all matches of the Dutch national team jointly on large screens at the Museumplein.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] During the 2014 World Cup the Oranjeplein was however after the eighth finals no longer held since the times of the matches that followed because of the time difference with Brazil were too late and the inconvenience was too large for local residents.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] During the semi-finals, however, it organized an Oranjeplein again, but in a different location, the Arena Park, next to the Amsterdam Arena.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 broadcasts during The Voice of Holland together with RTL 4 the live shows of the talent.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] An annual item *Hier met je rekening!* (English: Here with your bill!).
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] With this action 538 pays the accounts of listeners.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] To join it, the listener must send an email with a copy of the bill plus the description and amount of the bill.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The account can also be uploaded on the website of Radio 538 using a special form which is for and during the action to find on this site.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The entries will be once per hour a name called.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The person who is involved should then call to the studio within fifteen minutes, then his or her account is paid (Radio 538 then makes the total amount of the account to the account of the listener so that it can pay on account of this).
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] From 2014 538 also pays bills via Twitter.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On the Twitter page of Radio 538 during the action a submitted bill appears and the one who recognizes this bill must then retweet within fifteen minutes, after which the bill will be paid.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 assists over here to pay them a hand by these accounts.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Here there is a secret person, better known as Mr.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Every day, he is at a different location.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On which location the listener gets little tips on the radio.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The listener who finds on this basis Mr.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] If he was somewhere he sticks a sticker to and tells at the end of the day where he has been.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] During the action the money was collected for War Child, an organization designed to help children cope with their war trauma.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Listeners of the radio station came up with the stunts that were done during the week of action, and that money was raised.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Every day was 538 with a mobile studio on a different place in the Netherlands.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The places where 538 in 2012 was a guest was: Maastricht, 's-Hertogenbosch, Nijmegen, Hilversum, Alphen aan den Rijn, Meppel, Leeuwarden and Groningen.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Performances were given by, among other Pearl Jozefzoon, Glennis Grace, Hardwell, Ben Saunders, Iris Kroes, VanVelzen, Ferry Corsten, Destine, Waylon, Di-rect, Charly Luske, Racoon, Lange Frans and Xander de Buisonjé.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 2013, 538 was a guest in: Groningen, Heerenveen, Alkmaar, Gouda, Bergen op Zoom, Veenendaal, Arnhem and 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On 1 May 2013 it was announced that 538 stops 538 for War Child.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Radio 538 was founded in 1992 by Lex Harding.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In 1995 Lex Harding founded the TV channel TMF (*The Music Factory*).
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Both stations aired from the same building and worked together a lot.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Erik de Zwart became the new director of Radio 538.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In late 2002 Erik de Zwart moved to Talpa Radio International.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In December 2003, Radio 538 was sold to the investment fund Advent International.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On 23 May 2005 Radio 538 was fully acquired by Talpa by John de Mol and Lex Harding took definitely goodbye.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Together with Radio 10 Gold, which already owned by Talpa, Radio 538 was brought under the management of Talpa Radio (since 2006: Talpa Media).
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Until that moment, Talpa, next to Radio 10 Gold, also owned Noordzee FM.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] Because it was not allowed under the provisions of the 2003 frequency to two general, possess national commercial radio broadcasters, Talpa was forced to sell Noordzee FM.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] The Flemish company De Persgroep took Noordzee FM and renamed the station few months later to Q-music.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] De Persgroep does not have to pay anything for Noordzee FM to Talpa.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On 1 October 2007 Radio 538, along with various programs from the television channel Tien was taken over by RTL Nederland.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] On 1 January 2012 Radio 538 was, like its sister stations Radio 10 Gold and Slam!FM, taken over again by Talpa Holding.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] This was a result of a transaction between RTL Group and Talpa Holding, which has been an exchange of shares and sale to the order.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] RTL Group owned back all shares in RTL Nederland Holding since 1 January 2015, while Talpa became again the 100% owner of Radio 538.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] All this is a result of participation by Talpa Holding in SBS Broadcasting.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] TV 538 is a television channel which started in 2011 as a TV channel of Radio 538.
[src:2-unlimited/538-radio-station] In addition, the station has a number of digital channels that link to Radio 538, like 53L8, 538NL and 538IBIZA.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The 2014 calendar consisted of six race weekends.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] However, Acceleration in Zolder, Acceleration at Paul Ricard, and Acceleration at Grobnik were cancelled on 27 June 2014 and Acceleration at Hungaroring was cancelled on 21 August 2014.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] Their drivers may have been a different nationality, but the car represented the country.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The winning driver/team was entitled to the full budget for the 2015 FA1 season and a test day in the GP2 Series car in Abu Dhabi.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] All cars were mechanically identical and had been built with reducing costs in mind, which led to an approximate price for the whole season of €450,000.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] FA1 used the Lola B05/52, which had been used in the A1 Grand Prix between 2005 and 2008.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The starting order of race 3 was decided by a combined result of Q1 and Q2 with the first 8 reversed.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] For race 1 and 2, the top 10 finishers scored points in the following order: 20, 15, 12, 10, 8, 6, 4, 3, 2, 1.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The drivers' champion was entitled to a test day in the 2015 FA1 car plus either half the budget for the 2015 FA1 season or the full budget for the 2015 MW-V6 season.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The cars were based on those used in the Dutch racing series BRL V6 and BRL Light.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] Their drivers may have been a different nationality, but the car, whose design was derived from legends car racing, represented the country.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The winning driver/team was entitled to a test day in the 2015 MW-V6 car and half the budget for the 2015 MW-V6 season.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] Lots were drawn by the drivers during the briefing to determine the starting grid for Sprint Race 1.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The starting grid for Sprint Race 2 was the reversed Race 1 starting grid.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The starting grid for Sprint Race 3 corresponded to the points scored in Races 1 and 2 (the driver who had scored the highest number of points started on the pole).
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] In the case of even results when adding points of races 1 and 2, the fastest lap of races 1 and 2 was to decide between the drivers.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] The cars were based on those used in legends car racing.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] Each ACC 600 and ACC 1000 team represented a nation.
[src:2-unlimited/acceleration-2014] Their drivers may have been a different nationality, but the motorcycle represented the country.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] AllMusic was launched as *All-Music Guide* by Michael Erlewine, a "compulsive archivist, noted astrologer, Buddhist scholar, and musician." He became interested in using computers for his astrological work in the mid-1970s and founded a software company, Matrix, in 1977.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In the early 1990s, as compact discs (CDs) replaced LPs and cassettes as the dominant format for recorded music, Erlewine purchased what he thought was a CD of early recordings by Little Richard.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] After buying it, he discovered it was a "flaccid latter-day rehash." Frustrated with the labeling, he researched using metadata to create a music guide.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In 1990, in Big Rapids, Michigan, he founded *All Music Guide* with a goal to create an open-access database that included every recording "since Enrico Caruso gave the industry its first big boost".
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] The first *All Music Guide*, published in 1992, was a 1,200-page reference book, packaged with a CD-ROM, titled *All Music Guide: The Best CDs, Albums & Tapes: The Expert's Guide to the Best Releases from Thousands of Artists in All Types of Music*.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] Its first online version, in 1994, was a text-based Gopher site.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] It moved to the World Wide Web as web browsers became more user-friendly.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] Erlewine hired a database engineer, Vladimir Bogdanov, to design the *All Music Guide* framework, and recruited his nephew, writer Stephen Thomas Erlewine, to develop editorial content.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In 1993, Chris Woodstra joined the staff as an engineer.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] A "record geek" who had written for alternative weeklies and fanzines, his main qualification was an "encyclopedic knowledge of music".
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] AllMusic developed a list of 1,400 subgenres of music, a feature that became central to the site's utility.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In a 2016 article in *Tedium*, Ernie Smith wrote, "AllMusic may have been one of the most ambitious sites of the early-internet [sic] era—and it's one that is fundamental to our understanding of pop culture.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] Because the thing is, it doesn't just track reviews or albums.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] It tracks styles, genres, and subgenres, along with the tone of the music and the platforms on which the music is sold.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In 1996, seeking to further develop its web-based businesses, Alliance Entertainment Corp. bought All Music from Erlewine for a reported $3.5 million.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] Alliance filed for bankruptcy in 1999, and its assets were acquired by Ron Burkle's Yucaipa Equity Fund.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In 1999, All Music relocated from Big Rapids to Ann Arbor, Michigan, where the staff expanded from 12 to 100 people.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] By February of that year, 350,000 albums and two million tracks had been cataloged.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In late 2007, AllMusic was purchased for $72 million by TiVo Corporation (known as Macrovision at the time of the sale and as Rovi from 2009 until 2016).
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In 2012, AllMusic removed all of Bryan Adams' info from the site per a request from the artist.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In 2015, AllMusic was purchased by BlinkX, later known as RhythmOne.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] The AllMusic database is powered by a combination of MySQL and MongoDB.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] The All Media Network produced the *All Music Guide: The Definitive Guide* (at first released as *The Experts' Guide*), which includes a series of publications about various music genres.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] It was followed by the *Required Listening* series and annual guides.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] Vladimir Bogdanov is the president and the main editor of the series.
[src:2-unlimited/allmusic] In August 2007, *PC Magazine* included AllMusic in its "Top 100 Classic Websites" list.
[src:2-unlimited/altsounds] In 2024, the original domain AltSounds.com became a music video database.
[src:2-unlimited/altsounds] The website was originally created in 2004 by editor-in-chief Chris "MUG5" Maguire.
[src:2-unlimited/altsounds] AltSounds published content from different contributors including, academics and professional journalists to career professionals and first time writers.
[src:2-unlimited/altsounds] It included news, interviews, record reviews, as well competitions.
[src:2-unlimited/altsounds] In June 2008, the website formed a record label, Altsounds Records, signing Winch House as their first act.
[src:2-unlimited/altsounds] In November 2012, AltSounds was added to the list of ratings sources of AnyDecentMusic?.
[src:2-unlimited/altsounds] In 2015, the format of the magazine format was changed to video streaming only.
[src:2-unlimited/altsounds] In 2016, Maguire founded the creative marketing agency RIOT.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It is best known as the world's biggest online shopping retailer and marketplace, offering a wide range of products and services.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon sells books, electronics, pharmaceuticals, car parts, video games, dining products, jewelry, food, music, and sports equipment.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The company has multiple subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services (AWS), which provides cloud computing; Zoox, a self-driving car division; Kuiper Systems, a satellite Internet provider; and Amazon Lab126, a computer hardware R&D provider.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Other subsidiaries include Ring, Twitch, IMDb, and Whole Foods Market.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Its acquisition of Whole Foods in August 2017 for US$13.4 billion substantially increased its market share and its presence as a physical retailer.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also distributes a variety of downloadable and streaming content through its Amazon Prime Video, MGM+, Amazon Music, Twitch, Audible, and Wondery units.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also produces consumer electronics, most notably Kindle e-readers, Echo devices, Fire tablets, and Fire TVs.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has a reputation as a disruptor of industries through technological innovation and aggressive reinvestment of profits into capital expenditures.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of 2023, it is the world's largest online retailer and marketplace, smart speaker provider, cloud computing service provider through AWS, live-streaming service provider through Twitch, and Internet company as measured by revenue and market share.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2021, it surpassed Walmart as the world's largest retailer outside of China, driven in large part by its paid subscription plan, Amazon Prime, which has 200 million subscribers worldwide.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It is the second-largest private employer in the United States and the second-largest company in the world and the United States by revenue as of 2024 (after Walmart).
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of October 2024, Amazon is the 12th-most visited website in the world, and 84% of its traffic comes from the United States.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has been criticized for its business practices, including surveillance partnerships, poor working conditions, anti-union efforts, environmental harm, anticompetitive behavior, censorship controversies, and exploitative treatment of small businesses and suppliers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On July 5, 1994, Amazon was founded as "Cadabra" by Jeff Bezos, after he relocated from New York City to Bellevue, Washington, near Seattle, to operate an online bookstore.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Bezos chose the Seattle area for its abundance of technical talent from Microsoft and the University of Washington, as well as its smaller population for sales tax purposes and the proximity to a major book distribution warehouse in Roseburg, Oregon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Other options Bezos considered included Portland, Oregon, and Boulder, Colorado.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] A few months later, in November 1994, Cadabra, which had been founded in the converted garage of Bezos's house for symbolic reasons, was renamed to Amazon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On July 16, 1995, the Amazon website launched for public sales, initially sourcing its books directly from wholesalers and publishers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Bezos retained the URL www.relentless.com, which he purchased when considering a name for the company; it redirects to the Amazon homepage.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 1998, Amazon began selling music and videos, and began international operations by acquiring online sellers of books in the United Kingdom and Germany.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In the subsequent year, it initiated the sale of a diverse range of products, including music, video games, consumer electronics, home improvement items, software, games, and toys.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2002, the company launched Amazon Web Services (AWS), which initially focused on providing APIs for web developers to build web applications on top of Amazon's e-commerce platform.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2004, AWS was expanded to provide website popularity statistics and web crawler data from the Alexa Web Information Service.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] AWS later shifted toward providing enterprise services with Simple Storage Service (S3) in 2006, and Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) in 2008, allowing companies to rent data storage and computing power from Amazon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2006, Amazon launched the*Fulfillment by Amazon*program, which allowed individuals and small companies (called "third-party sellers") to sell products through Amazon's warehouses and fulfillment infrastructure.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon purchased the Whole Foods Market supermarket chain in 2017.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It is the leading e-retailer in the United States with approximately US$178 billion net sales in 2017.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It has over 300 million active customer accounts globally.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon saw large growth during the COVID-19 pandemic, hiring more than 100,000 staff in the United States and Canada.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Some Amazon workers in the US, France, and Italy protested the company's decision to "run normal shifts" due to COVID-19's ease of spread in warehouses.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In Spain, the company faced legal complaints over its policies, while a group of US Senators wrote an open letter to Bezos expressing concerns about workplace safety.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On February 2, 2021, Bezos announced that he would step down as CEO to become executive chair of Amazon's board.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The transition officially took place on July 5, 2021, with former CEO of AWS Andy Jassy replacing him as CEO.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In January 2023, Amazon cut over 18,000 jobs, primarily in consumer retail and its human resources division in an attempt to cut costs.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On November 8, 2023, a plan was adopted for Jeff Bezos to sell approximately 50 million shares of the company over the next year with a deadline of January 31, 2025.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The first step was the sale of 12 million shares for about $2 billion.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On February 26, 2024, Amazon became a component of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On December 19, 2024, Amazon workers, led by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters labor union, went on strike against Amazon in at least four US states, with workers in other facilities in the United States being welcomed to join the strike as well.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On October 28, 2025, the company announced plans to reduce its corporate workforce by 14,000 positions, which has been reported as the largest round of job cuts by Amazon since 2022.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As part of this plan, Amazon is expected to fire about 370 people from its European headquarters in Luxembourg in December 2025 to early 2026.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced a second round of large-scale layoffs, affecting approximately 16,000 corporate employees.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] This followed the earlier reduction of 14,000 positions in October 2025.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] According to company statements and news reports, the layoffs were part of a broader effort to streamline operations, reduce bureaucracy, and adapt to changing business conditions, including the adoption of artificial intelligence technologies.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Affected employees were offered severance packages and support for internal job placement.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In January 2025, Amazon filed an objection to Saks Global’s bankruptcy financing plan.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon invested $475 million into Saks’ acquisition of Neiman Marcus, and is now worried that Saks declaring bankruptcy would harm creditors and push the tech company further down the repayment pecking order.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon entered talks with OpenAI to invest up to $50 billion.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon historically has a deep strategic partnership with Anthropic, OpenAI's competitor.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon also laid off 16,000 employees in what is Amazon's second round of large-scale job reductions in three months due to AI.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In March 2026, Amazon signed an energy pledge at the White House which required it to bear the cost of new electricity generation to power its data centers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon launched Amazon Supply Chain Services in May 2026.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon websites are country-specific (for example, amazon.com for the US and amazon.co.uk for UK) though some offer international shipping.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Visits to *amazon.com* grew from 615 million annual visitors in 2008, to more than 2 billion per month in 2022.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The e-commerce platform is the 12th most visited website in the world.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In February 2024, Amazon announced its first chatbot, "Rufus", for use in the US; in July it was widely available to all customers in the US.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] "Rufus" is now available in the US, India and the UK which helps the shoppers get product recommendations, get shopping list advice, compare products and see what other customers have responded to regarding their specific questions.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Results generated by Amazon's search engine are partly determined by promotional fees.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2004, Toys "R" Us sued Amazon, claiming that because of a perceived lack of variety in Toys "R" Us stock, Amazon had knowingly allowed third-party sellers to offer items on the service in categories that Toys "R" Us had been granted exclusivity.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2006, a court ruled in favor of Toys "R" Us, giving it the right to unwind its agreement with Amazon and establish its independent e-commerce website.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The company was later awarded $51 million in damages.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2001, Amazon entered into a similar agreement with Borders, under which Amazon would comanage Borders.com as a co-branded service.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Borders pulled out of the arrangement in 2007, with plans to also launch its own online store.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On October 18, 2011, Amazon.com announced a partnership with DC Comics for the exclusive digital rights to many popular comics, including *Superman*, *Batman*, *Green Lantern*, *Sandman*, and *Watchmen*.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The partnership has caused well-known bookstores like Barnes & Noble to remove these titles from its shelves.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In November 2013, Amazon announced a partnership with the United States Postal Service to begin delivering orders on Sundays.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The service, included in Amazon's standard shipping rates, initiated in metropolitan areas of Greater Los Angeles and New York because of the high-volume and inability to deliver in a timely way, with plans to expand into Dallas, Houston, New Orleans and Phoenix by 2014.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In June 2017, Nike agreed to sell products through Amazon in exchange for better policing of counterfeit goods.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] This proved unsuccessful and Nike withdrew from the partnership in November 2019.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Companies including IKEA and Birkenstock also stopped selling through Amazon around the same time, citing similar frustrations over business practices and counterfeit goods.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In September 2017, Amazon ventured with one of its sellers JV Appario Retail owned by Patni Group which has recorded a total income of US$104.44 million (₹759 crore) in financial year 2017–2018.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of October 11, 2017, Amazon Fresh sold a range of Booths branded products for home delivery in selected areas.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In November 2018, Amazon reached an agreement with Apple Inc. to sell selected products through the service, via the company and selected Apple Authorized Resellers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As a result of this partnership, only Apple Authorized Resellers may sell Apple products on Amazon effective January 4, 2019.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On November 7, 2024, Amazon is reportedly discussing a second multi-billion dollar investment in AI startup Anthropic, following its initial $4 billion investment.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On 8 October 2025, Amazon launched prescription vending machines at One Medical clinics in Los Angeles.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The machines are operated by Amazon Pharmacy and are able to prescribe a range of common medications, such as antibiotics, inhalers and blood pressure treatments.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon sells many products under its own brand names, including phone chargers, batteries, and diaper wipes.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The AmazonBasics brand was introduced in 2009, and now features hundreds of product lines, including smartphone cases, computer mice, batteries, dumbbells, and dog crates.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon owned 34 private-label brands as of 2019.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] These brands account for 0.15% of Amazon's global sales, whereas the average for other large retailers is 18%.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Other Amazon retail brands include Presto!, Mama Bear, and Amazon Essentials.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon derives many of its sales (around 40% in 2008) from third-party sellers who sell products on Amazon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Some other large e-commerce sellers use Amazon to sell their products in addition to selling them through their websites.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The sales are processed through Amazon.com and end up at individual sellers for processing and order fulfillment and Amazon leases space for these retailers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Small sellers of used and new goods go to Amazon Marketplace to offer goods at a fixed price.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Publishers can sign up as affiliates and receive a commission for referring customers to Amazon by placing links to Amazon on their websites if the referral results in a sale.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Worldwide, Amazon has "over 900,000 members" in its affiliate programs.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of mid-2014, the Amazon Affiliate Program was used by 1.2% of all websites and was the second most popular advertising network after Google Ads.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It is frequently used by websites and non-profits to provide a way for supporters to earn them a commission.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Associates can access the Amazon catalog directly on their websites by using the Amazon Web Services (AWS) XML service.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] A new affiliate product, aStore, allows Associates to embed a subset of Amazon products within another website, or linked to another website.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In June 2010, Amazon Seller Product Suggestions was launched to provide more transparency to sellers by recommending specific products to third-party sellers to sell on Amazon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Products suggested are based on customers' browsing history.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon allows users to submit reviews to the web page of each product.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Reviewers must rate the product on a rating scale from one to five stars.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon provides a badging option for reviewers that indicates the real name of the reviewer (based on confirmation of a credit card account) or that indicates that the reviewer is one of the top reviewers by popularity.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of 16 December 2020, Amazon removed the ability of sellers and customers to comment on product reviews and purged their websites of all posted product review comments.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In an email to sellers, Amazon gave its rationale for removing this feature: "...the comments feature on customer reviews was rarely used." The remaining review response options are to indicate whether the reader finds the review helpful or to report that it violates Amazon policies (abuse).
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] If a review is given enough "helpful" hits, it appears on the front page of the product.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2010, Amazon was reported as being the largest single source of Internet consumer reviews.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] When publishers asked Bezos why Amazon would publish negative reviews, he defended the practice by claiming that Amazon.com was "taking a different approach...we want to make every book available—the good, the bad and the ugly...to let truth loose".
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] There have been cases of positive reviews being written and posted by public relations companies on behalf of their clients and instances of writers using pseudonyms to leave negative reviews of their rivals' works.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The Amazon sales rank (ASR) indicates the popularity of a product sold on any Amazon locale.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It is a relative indicator of popularity that is updated hourly.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Effectively, it is a "best sellers list" for the millions of products stocked by Amazon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] While the ASR has no direct effect on the sales of a product, it is used by Amazon to determine which products to include in its bestsellers lists.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Products that appear in these lists enjoy additional exposure on the Amazon website and this may lead to an increase in sales.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In particular, products that experience large jumps (up or down) in their sales ranks may be included within Amazon's lists of "movers and shakers"; such a listing provides additional exposure that might lead to an increase in sales.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] For competitive reasons, Amazon does not release actual sales figures to the public.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] However, Amazon has now begun to release point of sale data via the BookScan service to verified authors.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] While the ASR has been the source of much speculation by publishers, manufacturers, and marketers, Amazon itself does not release the details of its sales rank calculation algorithm.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In November 2015, Amazon opened a physical Amazon Books store in University Village in Seattle.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The store was 5,500 square feet and prices for all products matched those on its website.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon opened its tenth physical bookstore in 2017; media speculation at the time suggested that Amazon planned to eventually roll out 300 to 400 bookstores around the country.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] All of its locations were closed in 2022 along with other retail locations under the "Amazon 4-Star" brand.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In July 2016, the company announced that it was opening a 1,100,000 ft (335,280.0 m) square foot facility in Palmer Township in the Lehigh Valley region of eastern Pennsylvania.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of 2024, Amazon is the Lehigh Valley region's third-largest employer.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In August 2019, Amazon applied to have a liquor store in San Francisco, as a means to ship beer and alcohol within the city.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2020, Amazon Fresh opened several physical stores in the US and the United Kingdom.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced it would close all of its Amazon Go and Amazon Fresh stores to shift focus to its online same-day delivery service and expand its Whole Foods Market business.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The closure affects 57 Fresh stores and 15 Amazon Go locations, some of which will be converted into Whole Foods stores.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has a number of products and services available, including its digital assistant Alexa, Amazon Music, and Prime Video for music and videos respectively, the Amazon Appstore for Android apps, the Kindle line of electronic paper e-readers, Fire and Fire HD color LCD tablets.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Audible provides audiobooks for purchase and listening.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In September 2021, Amazon announced the launch of Astro, its first household robot, powered by its Alexa smart home technology.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] This can be remote-controlled when not at home, to check on pets, people, or home security.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It will send owners a notification if it detects something unusual.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In January 2023, Amazon announced the launch of RXPass, a prescription drug delivery service.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Prime members to pay a $5 monthly fee for access to 60 medications.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The service was launched immediately after the announcement except in states with specific prescription delivery requirements.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Beneficiaries of government healthcare programs such as Medicare and Medicaid will not be able to sign up for RXPass.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon owns over 100 subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services, Audible, Diapers.com, Goodreads, IMDb, Kiva Systems (now Amazon Robotics), One Medical, Shopbop, Teachstreet, Twitch, Zappos, and Zoox.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Bezos separately owns *The Washington Post* (through Nash Holdings, LLC), Blue Origin, Bezos Expeditions, Altos Labs, and other companies.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Live is a video e-commerce live-streaming service created to compete with live-streaming services.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The service allows users to stream live videos promoting or sponsoring products.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Users (mainly celebrities or Internet influencers) have the option to livestream on Amazon and add tags to additionally add context to the products they're selling or promoting.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Other users can join in and type in messages to send to a global chat on the livestream.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2019 Amazon launched an integrated platform into the Amazon website and application.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In 2023 roughly a billion total viewers watch Amazon Live across the United States and India.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The platform has also been integrated into Amazon Freevee and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Web Services (AWS) is a subsidiary of Amazon that provides on-demand cloud computing platforms and APIs to individuals, companies, and governments, on a metered pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] These cloud computing web services provide distributed computing processing capacity and software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of 2021 Q4, AWS has 33% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 21%, and 10% respectively, according to Synergy Group.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Audible is a seller and producer of spoken audio entertainment, information, and educational programming on the Internet.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Audible sells digital audiobooks, radio and television programs, and audio versions of magazines and newspapers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Through its production arm, Audible Studios, Audible has also become the world's largest producer of downloadable audiobooks.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On January 31, 2008, Amazon announced it would buy Audible for about $300 million.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The deal closed in March 2008 and Audible became a subsidiary of Amazon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Goodreads is a "social cataloging" website founded in December 2006 and launched in January 2007 by Otis Chandler, a software engineer, and entrepreneur, and Elizabeth Khuri.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The website allows individuals to freely search Goodreads' extensive user-populated database of books, annotations, and reviews.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Users can sign up and register books to generate library catalogs and reading lists.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] They can also create their groups of book suggestions and discussions.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In December 2007, the site had over 650,000 members, and over a million books had been added.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon bought the company in March 2013.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Ring is a home automation company founded by Jamie Siminoff in 2013.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It is primarily known for its Wi-Fi powered smart doorbells, but manufactures other devices such as security cameras.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon bought Ring for US$1 billion in 2018.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Twitch is a live streaming platform for video, primarily oriented towards video gaming content.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Twitch was acquired by Amazon in August 2014 for $970 million.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The site's rapid growth had been boosted primarily by the prominence of major esports competitions on the service, leading *GameSpot* senior esports editor Rod Breslau to have described the service as "the ESPN of esports".
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of 2015, the service had over 1.5 million broadcasters and 100 million monthly viewers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Whole Foods Market is an American supermarket chain exclusively featuring foods without artificial preservatives, colors, flavors, sweeteners, and hydrogenated fats.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon acquired Whole Foods for $13.7 billion in August 2017.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Since acquiring Whole Foods, the company has launched its own chain of Fresh supermarkets and taken steps to integrate its online and physical grocery operations.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also has investments in renewable energy, including plans to fund four small nuclear reactors at the Xe-100 reactor site in Eastern Washington, and plans to expand its position into the Canadian market through an investment in a new plant in Alberta.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's global headquarters are in more than 40 owned and leased buildings spread across Seattle's adjacent South Lake Union, Denny Triangle, and Downtown neighborhoods.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The first 14 buildings Amazon occupied in South Lake Union were developed primarily by Vulcan, Inc. from 2008 onward, the first 11 of which were acquired from Vulcan in 2012 at a cost of $1.16 billion.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The company was previously headquartered in rented space within the Pacific Medical Center, located in the city's Beacon Hill neighborhood, from 1998 to 2011.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon is currently building a new four tower, four low-rise, complex in Seattle's Denny Triangle neighborhood to serve as the primary headquarters, though it will retain many of the earlier purchased buildings to house its more than 45,000 corporate employees in the Seattle area.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The plan for the new campus, designed by NBBJ and named "Rufus 2.0" after a dog who was a fixture of the company in its early days, was approved by the city of Seattle in 2012 and construction began the year after.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The first of the towers, nicknamed Doppler, opened on December 14, 2015.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's European headquarters are in Luxembourg's capital, Luxembourg.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Its UK headquarters are at Principal Place, Shoreditch, London.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On November 13, 2018, Amazon announced that it would divide the planned HQ2 between New York City and Northern Virginia.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On February 14, 2019, Amazon canceled its plan for the HQ2 location in New York City.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon is also in the process of building a retail hub of operations center in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On August 21, 2019, Amazon opened its largest campus in the world at Nanakramguda in Hyderabad, India.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] It is the first Amazon-owned campus located outside the United States and features the single largest Amazon-owned building in the world.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The 9.5-acre campus houses over 15,000 employees.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon plans to build a major campus in Bellevue, Washington, a suburb of Seattle, that will host 15,000 employees by 2025.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The company opened its first Bellevue office in 2017, marking a return to the city since the company was founded there in 1995.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's largest building in the city is Sonic, a 42-story building developed by Vulcan Real Estate with 1 million square feet (93,000 m2) of office space.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The Bellevue campus will include the 43-story Bellevue 600 tower, which is planned to be the tallest building in the city and the tallest to be developed by Amazon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] While much of Amazon's software development occurs in Seattle, the company employs software developers in centers across the globe.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Some of these sites are run by an Amazon subsidiary called A2Z Development.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has operated various retail store brands.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Most of the stores are located inside of the United States, but Whole Foods also operates stores in Canada and the United Kingdom, while Amazon Go has six locations in London under the Amazon Fresh name.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon uses many different transportation services to deliver packages.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon directly employs people to work at its warehouses, bulk distribution centers, staffed "Amazon Hub Locker+" locations, and delivery stations where drivers pick up packages.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] As of December 2020, it is not hiring delivery drivers as employees.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Rakuten Intelligence estimated that in 2020 in the United States, the proportion of last-mile deliveries was 56% by Amazon's directly contracted services (mostly in urban areas), 30% by the United States Postal Service (mostly in rural areas), and 14% by UPS.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In April 2021, Amazon reported to investors it had increased its in-house delivery capacity by 50% in the last 12 months (which included the first year of the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States).
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In addition to Amazon Lockers, Amazon has around 30 staffed pickup points in the United States and over 800 independent ones in India.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The US locations have large sets of Amazon Lockers and an area for customers to make returns.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The India locations are in existing retailers and have customers wait for a store employee to retrieve their package.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon first launched its distribution network in 1997 with two fulfillment centers in Seattle and New Castle, Delaware.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has several types of distribution facilities consisting of cross-dock centers, fulfillment centers, sortation centers, delivery stations, Prime now hubs, and Prime air hubs.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] There are 75 fulfillment centers and 25 sortation centers with over 125,000 employees.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Employees are responsible for five basic tasks: unpacking and inspecting incoming goods; placing goods in storage and recording their location; picking goods from their computer recorded locations to make up an individual shipment; sorting and packing orders; and shipping.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] A computer that records the location of goods and maps out routes for pickers plays a key role: employees carry hand-held computers which communicate with the central computer and monitor their rate of progress.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Some warehouses are partially automated with systems built by Amazon Robotics.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In September 2006, Amazon launched a program called FBA (Fulfillment By Amazon) whereby it could handle storage, packing and distribution of products and services for small sellers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers are large facilities with hundreds of employees, sometimes thousands.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] A picker may walk 10 or more miles a day.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In newer fulfillment centers, items are stored on pods and brought to pickers by robots (Amazon Robotics).
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In the United Kingdom, initial staffing was provided by Randstad NV and other temporary employment agencies.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In the United States, many workers are hired as Amazon employees and granted shares of stock or sign-on bonuses, while others are offered temporary seasonal positions.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] "When we have permanent positions available, we look to the top-performing temporary associates to fill them," said an Amazon spokesperson.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon acquired Kiva Systems, a warehouse automation company, in 2012.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers can also provide warehousing and order-fulfillment for third-party sellers, for an extra fee.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] Third-party sellers can use Fulfillment by Amazon (FBA) to ship for other platforms as well, such as eBay or their own websites.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] On March 20, 2020, Amazon agreed to remove metal detectors from its warehouses after a warehouse worker tested positive for COVID-19.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] In addition to removing metal detectors, Amazon enacted a "6 feet rule", which enforced a six-feet distance between warehouse employees.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p01] The Federal Public Health Emergency (PHE) for COVID-19 (which included social distancing) declared under Section 319 of the Public Health Service (PHS) Act, expired at the end of the day on May 11, 2023.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com is primarily a retail site with a sales revenue model; Amazon takes a small percentage of the sale price of each item that is sold through its website while also allowing companies to advertise their products by paying to be listed as featured products.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] As of 2018, Amazon.com is ranked eighth on the Fortune 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In Forbes Global 2000 2023 Amazon ranked 36th.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] For the fiscal year 2021, Amazon reported earnings of US$33.36 billion, with an annual revenue of US$469.82 billion, an increase of 21.7% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Since 2007 sales increased from 14.835 billion to 469.822 billion, due to continued business expansion.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon's market capitalization went over US$1 trillion again in early February 2020 after the announcement of the fourth quarter 2019 results.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] During his tenure, Jeff Bezos had become renowned for his annual shareholder letters, which have gained similar notability to those of Warren Buffett.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] These annual letters gave an "invaluable window" into the famously "secretive" company, and revealed Bezos's perspectives and strategic focus.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] A common theme of these letters is Bezos's desire to instill customer-centricity (in his words, "customer obsession") at all levels of Amazon, notably by making all senior executives field customer support queries for a short time at Amazon call centers.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] He also read many emails addressed by customers to his public email address.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] One of Bezos's most well-known internal memos was his mandate for "all teams" to "expose their data and functionality" through service interfaces "designed from the ground up to be externalizable".
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] This process, commonly known as a service-oriented architecture (SOA), resulted in mandatory dogfooding of services that would later be commercialized as part of AWS.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon has used internal recognition programs such as the Just Do It Award to encourage employee initiative and experimentation.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon lobbies the United States federal government and state governments on multiple issues such as the enforcement of sales taxes on online sales, transportation safety, privacy and data protection and intellectual property.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] According to regulatory filings, Amazon.com focuses its lobbying on the United States Congress, the Federal Communications Commission and the Federal Reserve.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com spent roughly $3.5 million, $5 million and $9.5 million on lobbying, in 2013, 2014 and 2015, respectively.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In 2019, it spent $16.8 million and had a team of 104 lobbyists.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com was a corporate member of the American Legislative Exchange Council (ALEC) until it dropped membership following protests at its shareholders' meeting on May 24, 2012.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In 2014, Amazon expanded its lobbying practices as it prepared to lobby the Federal Aviation Administration to approve its drone delivery program, hiring the Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld lobbying firm in June.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon and its lobbyists have visited with Federal Aviation Administration officials and aviation committees in Washington, D.C. to explain its plans to deliver packages.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In September 2020 this moved one step closer with the granting of a critical certificate by the FAA.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] During the second Trump Administration, Amazon donated several times to various events and aspects of his presidency.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Along with several other major companies, Amazon donated $1 million to Trump's inaugural fund.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In April 2025, Amazon was a corporate sponsor of the White House Easter Egg Roll, after Donald Trump solicited corporate sponsors for the event for the first time.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In October 2025, Amazon was listed among the donors funding the construction of the White House State Ballroom.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon lobbies on climate policy internationally.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In the US, following Trump’s 2025 inauguration, Amazon began frequent engagements with the executive branch to advocate for permitting reform and energy development to support data center growth.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In July 2025, Amazon joined policymakers at the Pennsylvania Energy and Innovation Summit, where it supported the development of nuclear energy to meet growing electricity demand, and lobbied for permitting reform to support grid development nationwide.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] A December 2025 DeSmog article reported that the company’s sponsorship came alongside several organizations that had supported climate change denial, and a continued role for fossil fuels to meet growing energy demand.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Criticism has also concerned various decisions over whether to censor or publish content such as the WikiLeaks website, works containing libel, anti-LGBT merchandise, and material facilitating dog fighting, cockfighting, or pedophile activities.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] An article published by *Time* in the wake of social media website Parler's termination of service by Amazon Web Service highlights the power companies like Amazon now have over the internet.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In December 2011, Amazon faced a backlash from small businesses for running a one-day deal to promote its new Price Check app.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Shoppers who used the app to check prices in a brick-and-mortar store were offered a 5% discount to purchase the same item from Amazon.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Companies like Groupon, eBay and Taap have countered Amazon's promotion by offering $10 off from its products.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] The company has also faced accusations of putting undue pressure on suppliers to maintain and extend its profitability.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In 2019, Amazon banned selling skin-lightening products after pushback from Minnesota health and environmental activists.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In 2022, a lawsuit filed by state attorney-general Letitia James was dismissed by the New York state court of appeals.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] After the COVID-19 pandemic, Amazon faced criticism for complying, under pressure from the Biden Administration, to "reduce the visibility" of books critical of the COVID-19 vaccine, which was revealed after Rep.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Jim Jordan (acting on behalf of the House Judiciary Committee) subpoenaed emails between the company and the Biden Administration.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Amazon Prime has been criticized for its vehicles systemically double parking, blocking bike lanes, and otherwise violating traffic laws while dropping off packages, contributing to traffic congestion and endangering other road users.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Jane Friedman discovered six listings of books fraudulently using her name, on Amazon and Goodreads.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In 2024, following years of criticism for providing law enforcement footage in the custody of Ring (a home security company owned by Amazon) without a warrant, Ring has halted this practice.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] It received cautious praise from privacy-focused organizations such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation for this change.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In February 2025, Sky accused Amazon of not doing enough to prevent the piracy of its sports rights via "jailbroken" Fire Sticks.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Project Nimbus is a contract by which Amazon and Google provide Israel and its military with artificial intelligence, machine learning, and other cloud-computing services.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] The contract has been criticized by shareholders and employees concerned that the project may lead to abuses of Palestinian human rights in the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In October 2025, Amazon suspended an employee who posted messages to the company's Slack and wrote a letter to Andy Jassy criticizing Nimbus.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] On July 22, 2025, Amazon announced its plan to acquire San Francisco-based startup Bee AI.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] Bee produces a wristband, similar to most modern smartwatches, equipped with AI and microphones.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] The wristband is capable of providing summaries of conversations and reminders of tasks, effectively serving as a 24/7 note taker.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] News outlets criticize the fact that the devices saves transcripts, potentially utilizing it to train generative AI models which require vast quantities of data.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] In January 2026, Amazon sent a notice out to cloud staffers in an apparent error acknowledging “organizational changes” at the company.
[src:2-unlimited/amazon-company-p02] The note also mentioned a "Project Dawn" which was cancelled, although it is unclear what the project is about.
